05977nam a22006975i 9780804767293DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047672937 a10.1515/97808047672932doi  a(DE-B1597)581418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE183.8.J3bB5155 2004eb 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a327.7305222200aBeyond Bilateralism :bU.S.-Japan Relations in the New Asia-Pacific /ced. by Ellis S. Krauss, T. J. Pempel. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b11 tables, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Issues in Asia and the Pacific00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- t1. Challenges to Bilateralism: Changing Foes, Capital Flows, and Complex Forums -- tPART I. STRATEGY AND SECURITY -- t2. America in East Asia: Power, Markets, and Grand Strategy -- t3. U.S.-Japan Security Relations-Toward Bilateralism Plus? -- t4. Terms of Engagement: The U.S.-Japan Alliance and the Rise of China -- t5. American and Japanese Strategies in Asia: Dealing with ASEAN -- tPART II. ECONOMIC FLOWS -- t6. Capital Flows and Financial Markets in Asia: National, Regional, or Global? -- t7. When Strong Ties Fail: U.S.-Japanese Manufacturing Rivalry in Asia -- t8. Japan's Counterweight Strategy: U.S.- Japan Cooperation and Competition in International Finance -- t9. Japan and the Evolution of Regional Financial Arrangements in East Asia -- tPART III. MULTILATERAL ORGANIZATIONS -- t10. At Play in the Legal Realm: The WTO and the Changing Nature of U.S.-Japan Antidumping Disputes -- t11. Japan, the United States, and Multilateral Institution-Building in the Asia-Pacific: APEC and the ARF -- t12. The United States and Japan in APEC's EVSL Negotiations: Regional Multilateralism and Trade -- t13. Conclusion: Beyond Bilateralism- Toward Divided Dependence -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first comprehensive analysis of the ways in which changes in the geopolitical context have altered the nature of the long-stable U.S.-Japan relationship: much of what had once been a bilateral and relatively exclusive relationship has been transformed in the past two decades. The authors present eleven case studies of important domains—ranging from increased flows of private capital to international security concerns to the growing importance of multilateral organizations—in which the relationship has been altered to a greater or lesser degree. Individual chapters present new ways of understanding international financial flows, U.S.-Japan trade relations, and U.S.-Japan manufacturing rivalry. Others present very cogent synthetic analyses of the changing context of U.S.-Japan relations. Together they provide an account of the bilateral, regional, and global institutions—political, military, and financial—that dominate the geopolitics of U.S.-Asia relations. Although written to a consistently high intellectual level, the chapters in this timely volume are intended for a nonspecialist audience and will be useful to practitioners in business and government, as well as to students and teachers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aGeopolitics. 0aInternational agencies. 0aInternational economic relations. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 4aPolitics -- International Relations. 4aSecurity Studies -- Asian Security. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAmyx, Jennifer A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshizawa, Kuniko P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFukushima, Akiko,